To quantify this issue, we performed an exploratory analysis. We applied a fundamental physical filter to the CVAE-generated training samples, flagging any synthetic data point where the predicted thermal conductivity (k

                              eff
                           ) was lower than the corresponding base fluid's thermal conductivity (k

                              m
                           )—a physical impossibility. This check revealed that approximately 16.5 % of the CVAE samples for the Exp-TC target and 8.2 % for the KKL-TC target violated this basic physical bound.

For Experimental Thermal Conductivity (Exp-TC): The SHAP analysis for the CatBoost model revealed that the most influential features were, in descending order: thermal conductivity of the liquid (k

   m

), temperature (T), particle volume fraction (ϕ), thermal conductivity of the particle (k
p
), and particle size (d

   p

). This ranking aligns strongly with physical intuition. The dominant role of the base fluid's conductivity (km) is expected, as it forms the medium for heat transfer. The high importance of temperature reflects its known effect on enhancing Brownian motion and altering fluid viscosity, which are key mechanisms in nanofluid heat transfer.

For KKL-Model Thermal Conductivity (KKL-TC): The CatBoost feature importance for predicting KKL-TC was ranked as follows: particle volume fraction (ϕ), thermal conductivity of the liquid (k

   m

), temperature (T), thermal conductivity of the particle (k
p
), and particle size (d

   p

). The prominence of volume fraction (ϕ) is consistent with the KKL formulation, where it is a primary driver of both the static and Brownian conductivity components. The high importance of and is also expected, as these terms are explicit inputs to the KKL equations.
